<H3> <TI>   Geneva Hosts Bosnia Peace Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Geneva Hosts Bosnia Peace Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Croat Delegation Arrives </H4>

<F P=102> LD0206104994 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1000 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0206104994 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Jozo Curic from Geneva] </F>
  [Excerpt] The Bosnian Croats were again the first to agree 
to come to Geneva. Kresimir Zubak, president of the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina Federation, and Mile Akmadzic, foreign 
minister of the Croat republic of Herceg-Bosna, arrived in 
Geneva a few minutes ago. They were invited by Yasushi Akashi. 
There is no indication whether Federation Vice President Ejup 
Ganic, who represents the Bosnian Muslims at the cease-fire 
negotiations, will come. 
  Bearing in mind that all three sides have been invited to 
Geneva, it is not likely that Kresimir Zubak will be negotiating 
on behalf of the Federation, that is, of the two sides. Let us 
note that these talks today are not the negotiations on a 
general political solution to Bosnia-Herzegovina that are 
expected to resume in Geneva this coming weekend. This is the 
United Nation's attempt to mediate in a cease-fire between the 
Serbs and the Muslims, to make Mladic and Delic sign an 
agreement to disengage their forces. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

