<H3> <TI>   Geneva Hosts Bosnia Peace Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Geneva Hosts Bosnia Peace Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    UN: Serbs `Must Withdraw' From Gorazde </H4>

<F P=102> AU0206143194 Paris AFP in English 1414 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0206143194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, June 2 (AFP) -- The United Nations on 
Thursday ruled out peace negotiations on Bosnia as long as Serb 
forces remained in the eastern Bosnian enclave of Gorazde. UN 
special envoy Yasushi Akashi said "the Serbs must withdraw and 
until they do the talks will not proceed." But he added that 
the talks on a cessation of hostilities with the warring 
parties, which were to have started here on Thursday, could 
still get underway on Friday if the Serbs pulled out from the 
three-kilometre (two mile) exclusion zone around Gorazde. 
  Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic insisted in an 
interview 
with WTN that the Serb forces had withdrawn. "There were not 
many there. They left last night," he said. 

</TEXT>

