<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moravcik Condemns Opposition, Defends Minister </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moravcik Condemns Opposition, Defends Minister </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0106192894 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1000 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0106192894 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1000 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Slovak </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] This morning Prime Minister Jozef Moravcik met 
editors in chief of Slovak newspapers and directors of the 
electronic media. Under discussion were current political 
problems, on which the prime minister replied to numerous 
questions from representatives of the press. After the meeting, 
reporter Lydia Mrazova asked Jozef Moravcik for an interview. 
  [Begin recording] [Mrazova] Today is 77 days since you 
became 
prime minister in this government, and during this short time -- 
you could describe it as such -- the opposition has tried to 
dismiss Roman Kovac and Minister Janicina. Do you think will 
there yet be another? 
  [Moravcik] The tactics of the present opposition suggest 
that 
it will probably not stop playing this game, this destructive 
game, and that it will try to continue with it. I do not have 
any concrete information about who it might be. 
  [Mrazova] And what about fears? 
  [Moravcik] No fears, because until now the means of 
presentation tended to harm those presenting proposals for 
dismissal. 
  [Mrazova] According to what you said, although the coalition 
was formed with partners of differing orientations, the 
coalition is functioning well. During the vote of confidence 
vote in the minister for the administration and privatization it 
transpired that even deputies from the coalition parties 
contributed several votes in favor if his dismissal. Some 
expressed the view in the lobby that although they will not be 
voting for his dismissal they consider him to be the weakest 
point in the government. I do not expect you to criticize your 
minister, but how would you characterize this post? 
  [Moravcik] I have already said many times that privatization 
is a meeting point for a large number of conflicting interests 
and various organizations which exert various kinds of 
influence. What we call lobbies today are very strong. A 
minister in this position has to have a very firm character and 
also sound nerves because to manage all that, to resist all the 
pressures, and to organize and carry out privatization in such a 
way that it supports the government's policy is very demanding. 
It really is a very demanding position and I am satisfied with 
how the work is being carried out. So far, we have managed to 
overcome all the differences that have appeared, the different 
views that have appeared, which are entirely natural. [passage 
omitted] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

