<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trade Accord With Slovakia Ratified </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Trade Accord With Slovakia Ratified </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0106172394 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1400 
GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0106172394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Czech </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] With news of the 19th session of parliament's second 
day of business, here is Ivana Anyzova from the parliament 
building. 
  [Anyzova] The deputies of the Czech parliament today 
approved 
an agreement negotiated between the Czech Republic and the 
Republic of Slovakia concerning free trade. As Trade and 
Industry Minister Vladimir Dlouhy stated, this agreement will 
gradually liberalize bilateral trade, and by the end of the 
two-year transition period -- in other words by 1 January 1996 
-- all tariff and nontariff barriers to trade in all industrial 
products, with the exception of private cars and certain other 
items, will be removed. 
  Parliament also approved the statute of the National 
Property 
Fund of the Czech Republic [FNM]. According to this statute, the 
fund will have the right to set up joint-stock and trading 
companies and to invest in them. Following that, however, 
parliament did not approve the National Property Fund budget for 
1994. Three votes were lacking for the budget to be approved. 
The question thus presents itself whether parliament really has 
so much against it or whether the required number of deputies 
were not present at the final vote, in particular those from the 
governing coalition. At present, the deputies are debating the 
state's final accounts for last year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

