<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Krajisnik Comments on Serbian Assembly Session </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Krajisnik Comments on Serbian Assembly Session </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0106143094 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1300 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0106143094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Marica Lalovic from Pale] </F>
  [Text] The session of the people's assembly of the 
republic of Srpska continued behind closed doors in Pale this 
morning. The issues concerning the republic's domestic and 
foreign policy are again on the agenda today, the second day of 
the session. A report by the republican Defense Ministry is 
also on the agenda. The deputies are also expected to discuss 
the continuation of the peace negotiations on the former 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. The negotiations are scheduled to take 
place in Geneva tomorrow [2 June] and were called by Yasushi 
Akashi, special envoy of the UN Secretary General. 
  Commenting on his talks with [Russian Deputy Foreign 
Minister] Vitaliy Churkin yesterday, Momcilo Krajisnik, chairman 
of the people's assembly of the republic of Srpska, said on his 
arrival in Pale that the vital interests of the Serbian people 
are not for sale, and that the contact group and other 
international community's mediators in the talks on the former 
Bosnia-Herzegovina have already been made aware of that. 
  Krajisnik stressed that Churkin had said that the delegation 
of the Serbian Republic would travel to Geneva to attend the 
two-day talks on the former Bosnia-Herzegovina, but that this 
did not mean the continuation of the negotiations on the fate of 
the former Bosnia-Herzegovina, which the Serbian Republic is 
linking to the lifting of sanctions imposed on the Serbian 
people. 
  The special Russian envoy [Churkin] should arrive in 
Sarajevo 
today, where he will probably try to convince Alija Izetbegovic 
and the Muslim side that it is necessary for them to attend the 
negotiations in Geneva. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

