<DATE1>  1 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Slovak-Russian Agreement on Visa-Free Travel </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Slovak-Russian Agreement on Visa-Free Travel </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0106130694 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1000 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0106130694 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1000 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Slovak </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shortly before noon Slovak Foreign Minister Eduard 
Kukan and Russian Ambassador Sergey Yastrzhembskiy signed an 
agreement between the Government of the Slovak Republic and the 
Government of the Russian Federation on conditions for visa-free 
travel by citizens of the two states. Maria Mikusova has just 
returned from the Hotel Borik where the signing took place. 
  [Mikusova] This is the 27th agreement signed by Slovakia and 
Russia since the formation of an independent Slovakia and the 
first of its kind between Russia and one of the Visegrad Four 
countries. The existing arrangement of mutual relations in the 
sphere of travel created extensive possibilities for differences 
of interpretation and various bureaucratic measures. The 
signing of this agreement provides for the introduction of very 
precise and clear rules. In the words of Ambassador 
Yastrzhembskiy, it is a special agreement because it concerns 
people who are interested in visiting our country. 
  As for what the significance of this agreement was for 
Slovakia, I asked Slovak Foreign Minister Eduard Kukan: 
  [Begin recording] [Kukan] The agreement on visa-free travel 
which we signed with Ambassador Yastrzhembskiy has the principal 
significance of regulating travel and visits by Russian citizens 
here and our citizens to the Russian Federation. In terms of 
objective conditions it is not a classic agreement on visa-free 
travel such as we have with certain other European countries, 
but I think it will play a positive role in the current 
situation in our mutual relations and that it will have a 
positive effect on the future. It also documents our interest 
in expanding relations with the Russian Federation in such a way 
that would be beneficial to both sides. 
  [Mikusova] Minister, will this agreement guarantee that such 
elements as we would not wish to see here will not get onto our 
territory? 
  [Kukan] Yes. I answer yes unequivocally and without 
hesitation. That is why we signed it. [end recording] 
  Let me only add that the agreement will come into effect 
following joint ratification. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

