<H3> <TI>   Pawlak Views Economic Cooperation With Japan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pawlak Views Economic Cooperation With Japan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0106200494 Warsaw PAP in English 1848 GMT 1 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD0106200494 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, June 1 -- Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak 
emphasised Poland's need and desire for greater economic 
cooperation with Japan on Wednesday. Speaking after his meeting 
with the chairman of the Japan-Poland Economic Committee, 
Toshikuni Yahiro, he said that "Poland's good economic results 
will contribute to ensuring that it is based on partnership and 
will be beneficial to both sides." 
  Pawlak emphasised that Polish-Japanese trade was increasing. 
He recalled the important speech of Eijiro Hato, Japan's 
minister for international trade and industry, concerning the 
readiness of the Japanese Government to remove the barriers to 
short term trade loan and long term investment loan guarantees 
for Poland. 
  Toshikuni Yahiro said that the fifteenth session of the 
Polish-Japanese economic committees which had taken place after 
an almost four year break had opened up a new stage in 
cooperation between the two countries. He added that on his 
return to Japan he would urge his government to increase 
economic contacts with Poland. 
  Toshikuni Yahiro said that 1994 was a good year for 
strengthening economic links since Japan was beginning to 
recover from a three year recession and Poland had the best 
ecnomic results of all the central and east European countries. 

</TEXT>

