<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Krajisnik: Geneva Peace Talks Set for 4-5 Jun </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0306145794 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1300 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0306145794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The negotiations on a cease-fire in the former 
Bosnia-Herzegovina will be held at the French mission in Geneva 
on Saturday and Sunday [4 and 5 June]. This was stated for SRNA 
by Momcilo Krajisnik, chairman of the People's Assembly of the 
Serbian Republic [of Bosnia-Herzegovina]. As he said, he 
received this piece of information from Nikiforov, the Russian 
member of the contact group for the former Yugoslavia. 
  Yasushi Akashi, special UN envoy for the former Yugoslavia, 
who held talks with the delegation of the Serbian Republic, is 
trying to persuade all the warring sides to take part in the 
continuation of the peace talks, Momcilo Krajisnik said. He 
stressed that the Muslim delegation is abusing the problem of 
Gorazde for the umpteenth time in order to obstruct peace in the 
former Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  The representatives of the Serbian Republic should hold 
informal talks in Geneva with Charles Redman, U.S. envoy for the 
former Yugoslavia. 

