<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Commander: Serbian Forces Still in Gorazde </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Commander: Serbian Forces Still in Gorazde </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0306083094 Paris AFP in English 0755 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0306083094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Geneva, June 3 (AFP) -- Bosnian Serb forces 
remained within an UN-ordered exclusion zone around Gorazde 
Friday, blocking the resumption of truce talks here, the 
commander of UN forces in former Yugoslavia, General Bertrand de 
Lapresle, said. There were still "barely a few dozen in three 
pockets in the exclusion zone," he said. 
  UN officials have called for a meeting here with Bosnian 
Serb 
leader Radovan Karadzic to discuss the presence of around 150 
Serb forces in Gorazde. The Bosnian Government has demanded 
their complete withdrawal in compliance with an April 22 
ultimatum as a condition for their attending the talks, called 
to arrange an overall ceasefire throughout Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
Late Thursday a UN military spokesman said the Serbs had made 
no move to withdraw from the exclusion zone, contradicting an 
announcement by UN special envoy Yasushi Akashi that they had 
begun their pullout. 
  "There is no evidence at all that the Serbs are 
withdrawing," 
UN Protection Force spokesman Dacre Holloway said in Sarajevo. 
"Our information is that the situation is exactly the same," he 
said, charging that the armed Serb forces had merely donned 
civilian clothes and were pretending to be refugees while 
continuing to carry guns. 
  Negotiations due to have opened Thursday were postponed when 
it became clear that despite pledges from Karadzic that they 
would retreat the Bosnian Serb units had remained in place. 
Akashi on Thursday evening said the Serb forces had launched 
their withdrawal. "I have received positive news," he told AFP. 
"They have started their evacuation, but there are still some 
places where they have not moved." 
  Akashi's spokesman, Michael Williams, later added that about 
100 policemen had left the exclusion zone before nightfall. The 
reports were flatly contradicted by Major Holloway in Sarajevo. 
"The police and militia are wearing civilian clothes," he said. 
"But they are still carrying guns. They took their police 
uniforms off and claim to be refugees." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

