<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman: Serbs Begin Withdrawal From Gorazde </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Spokesman: Serbs Begin Withdrawal From Gorazde </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0306121194 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1132 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0306121194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Geneva, June 3 (TANJUG) -- The spokesman of the 
special U.N. envoy Yasushi Akashi, Micheal Williams, said Friday 
[3 June], quoting a telephone conversation with Gorazde, that 
the withdrawal of the Serb forces from the three kilometer 
exclusion zone around Gorazde, eastern Bosnia-Herzegovina, had 
started but that it was still not satisfactory. Williams told a 
press conference that cease-fire talks would not go ahead until 
the last element of the Serb militia, army and the last armed 
civilian of Serb nationality leaves the three-kilometer 
exclusion zone around Gorazde. He also said that the latest 
situation in the region was presently being discussed by 
UNPROFOR commanders for former Yugoslavia General Bertrand de 
Lapresle and for Bosnia-Herzegovina General Michael Rose with 
the officials of the Bosnian Serb Republic President Radovan 
Karadzic and bosnian Army Commander Ratko Mladic. 
  Williams told the press that two formations of Canadian blue 
helmets were dispatched from Sarajevo to Gorazde Friday morning 
as reinforcements to ensure that the demands for the Serbs 
withdrawal from the three-kilometer diameter are being complied 
with. According to Williams, the premier of the Muslim-Croat 
federation and head of the Muslim delegation Haris Silajdzic was 
currently in Paris. He did not specify if he was there for 
consultations. The vice-president of the Muslim-Croat 
federation Ejup Ganic, and the delegation accompanying him, is 
on his way to Zagreb and is due to reach Geneva Friday evening. 
  The Muslim delegation conditions its participation in the 
cease-fire talks with the withdrawal of the Serb forces from 
around Gorazde. If the Serbs withdraw Akashi could reschedule 
the cease-fire talks for Friday evening or Saturday morning, 
Williams said. If the cease-fire talks start on Saturday, the 
meeting of the contact group on the territorial division of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina between the warring Muslims, Serbs and 
Croats, scheduled for Saturday, will be postponed by 24 hours. 
  The meeting of the contact group with the Bosnian warring 
sides was initially scheduled for June 6 and 7 in Talloires, 
France, but the French Foreign Ministry Thursday postponed the 
meeting to June 4 and 5 in the French Embassy in Geneva. It 
could now be further postponed by another 24 hours. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

