<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic, Akashi Discuss Troops in Gorazde </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Karadzic, Akashi Discuss Troops in Gorazde </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0206202694 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1932 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0206202694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Geneva, 2 Jun -- Special UN envoy Yasushi Akashi 
had two hours of talks behind closed doors this evening in 
Geneva's Hotel Intercontinental with the delegation of the 
Bosnian Serb Republic. The delegation consisted of President 
Radovan Karadzic and General Ratko Mladic, commander in chief of 
the armed forces. TANJUG learned of the meeting from its sources 
in the Serb republic. Also attending the meeting was General 
Michael Rose, commander of the blue helmets in Bosnia, . 
  The topic of the talks was the question of the withdrawal of 
Serb forces from the 3-km zone around Gorazde, something which 
is being insisted upon by the Muslim side as a condition for 
participation in the Geneva conference. The continued presence 
of Serbs in the zone, as claimed by UN officials in Geneva is 
the reason for the fact that the Haris Silajdzic-led delegation 
failed to turn up for the opening of the conference on a 
comprehensive cease-fire, which had been scheduled to open today 
in Geneva. 
  According to Serb republic sources, Karadzic and Gen. Rose 
should inform Akashi late this evening whether the Serbs have 
withdrawn, as Karadzic has promised. 
  According to a statement of the Serb Republic Foreign 
Minister Buha given earlier this evening to TANJUG, there are 
prospects that the negotiations initiated by Akashi might 
nevertheless begin tomorrow. According to Buha, the Muslim 
delegation has arrived in Geneva and is having talks with the 
Croat delegation on the territorial division of the cantons in 
the newly-formed federation. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-31055 </DOCNO>
