<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meetings, Talks on Bosnia Continue in Geneva </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meetings, Talks on Bosnia Continue in Geneva </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Serbs `Willing' To Sign Cease-Fire </H4>

<F P=102> LD0506113394 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1102 GMT 5 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0506113394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Dragan Milosavljevic] </F>
  [Text] Geneva, June 5 (TANJUG) -- An atmosphere of 
uncertainity prevails at Geneva's Palais de Nations where the 
fourth day in a row is passing in the expectation of the 
decision by the Moslem delegation to finally take part in the 
talks on a ceasefire in the two-year war in the ex-Yugoslav 
republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  At 10:00 a.m. local time, when the several-times delayed 
talks were scheduled to begin on Sunday, the Bosnian Serb 
Republic (RS) delegation arrived headed by President Radovan 
Karadzic and military comander General Ratko Mladic. Karadzic 
told TANJUG that the Serb side is willing to sign a ceasefire. 
  The spokesman of the special U.N. envoy for the former 
Yugoslavia Yasushi Akashi on Sunday morning announced at a press 
conference that Akashi would meet for consultations with 
Moslem-Croat Federation Vice-President Ejup Ganic. Shortly 
afterward Ganic told journalists that the Serb forces had 
allegedly failed to withdraw from the 3-km exclusion zone in 
Gorazde and that the conditions for the start of the talks have 
still not been fulfilled. He thus tried to deny reports to the 
contrary by U.N. monitors from this Moslem enclave in eastern 
Bosnia. Akashi's spokesman Michael Williams could not say what 
the chances are for the talks starting on Sunday. 
  At the U.N. Geneva headquarters there are many skeptics who 
doubt that the Bosnian Moslems are ready for serious peace 
talks. Some believe that the entire affair aims to undermine 
the authority of Japanese diplomat Akashi whom the Moslems 
persistently and unfoundedly accuse of siding with the Serbs. 
  Williams also said that, according to his information, the 
first round of talks, sponsored by the "Contact Group," on a 
comprehensive political solution and territorial division in 
Bosnia, has been completed at the French U.N. mission. 
  Sources in the Bosnian Serb delegation said that the Serbs 
are dissatisfied by the maps proposed by the "Contact Group" in 
Washington because they are a basis for a unitary Bosnia, as 
adovcated by Moslem leader Alija Izetbegovic. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-31066 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu108aa_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
