<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meetings, Talks on Bosnia Continue in Geneva </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meetings, Talks on Bosnia Continue in Geneva </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Delegates Discuss Serb Withdrawal </H4>

<F P=102> LD0506150194 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1300 GMT 5 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0506150194 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Geneva talks on ending hostilities in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina have not yet begun because the Serb 
withdrawal from around Gorazde was not confirmed by 1400. Jozo 
Curic reports: 
  [Curic] There has been no change since the 1400 deadline, 
when the UN Protection Forces [UNPROFOR] were expected to 
confirm that the Serbs had withdrawn from two more points around 
Gorazde. 
  The Croat and Bosniak delegations, President Zubak, Minister 
Akmadzic, Prime Minister Silajdzic, and Vice President Ganic met 
in the Richmond Hotel in Geneva. New reports from Sarajevo say 
that nothing has changed on the ground. Negotiations on a 
four-month cease-fire in Bosnia-Herzegovina, initiated here in 
Geneva on 13 May by the foreign ministers of the great powers 
and the European Union, cannot begin. 
  Federation President Zubak and Vice President Ganic held 
talks this morning with Yasushi Akashi and Generals Rose and de 
Lapresle, who are unsuccessfully trying to get the talks 
started. The position of the joint Croat-Bosniak delegation in 
the talks was that UNPROFOR should present a report confirming 
there were no Serb forces in the 3-km zone around Gorazde. Vice 
President Ganic said that Butrus-Ghali's special envoy Yasushi 
Akashi had not presented a new UNPROFOR report from the Gorazde 
area to the Croat-Bosniak delegation by 1400. 
  Karadzic, Akashi, de Lapresle, and Rose held talks this 
morning, lasting for nearly an hour, but without any visible 
results. After the talks Radovan Karadzic said that the Muslims 
are sabotaging the talks on ending the hostilities. Intensive 
diplomatic efforts continue. UNPROFOR has confirmed the 
presence of Serb forces within 2,200 metres of the center of 
Gorazde. 

</TEXT>

