<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meetings, Talks on Bosnia Continue in Geneva </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meetings, Talks on Bosnia Continue in Geneva </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Karadzic, Ganic Agree to 6 Jun Talks </H4>

<F P=102> LD0506220494 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 2126 GMT 5 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0506220494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, 5 Jun (TANJUG) -- We have unofficially 
learned from sources close to the delegation of the Srpska 
republic that late tonight, in talks between Yasushi Akashi, UN 
special envoy for the former Yugoslavia, and representatives of 
the Serb and Muslim-Croat delegations, an agreement was 
eventually reached in principle to resume talks on a total 
cessation of hostilities in Bosnia. 
  These talks, as Radovan Karadzic and Ejup Ganic agreed, 
should start tomorrow at 1000 in the Palace of Nations in 
Geneva, the sources of the Serb republic say. The only 
precondition attached to this is a confirmation that "armed Serb 
elements" have withdrawn from the security zone, i.e. 3 km 
around Gorazde. 
  UN Secretary General Butrus-Ghali is expected to arrive in 
Geneva tonight. Akashi is believed to have invited the UN 
secretary general to help him in saving the conference and the 
reputation of the UN which is mediating in the peace talks. The 
Muslim delegation has for four days been finding reasons to 
delay the opening of the conference. 
  In all his contacts with the press Radovan Karadzic, head of 
the delegation of the Srpska republic, has been constantly 
saying: "We have come here to sign a peace and we do not set 
any conditions." 
  According to statements by Akashi's press officer, the 
conference has on several occasions been on the verge of being 
canceled. 

</TEXT>

