<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meetings, Talks on Bosnia Continue in Geneva </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meetings, Talks on Bosnia Continue in Geneva </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Muslims Confirm Serbian Withdrawal </H4>

<F P=102> LD0606095294 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 0908 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0606095294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, 6 Jun (TANJUG) -- The talks on an absolute 
cease-fire in Bosnia, which have been postponed since last 
Thursday, should begin in the Palais des Nations in Geneva soon. 
Yasushi Akashi's spokesman Michael Williams has officially 
confirmed that "all Serb elements have left the 3-km exclusion 
zone around Gorazde, as required by the UN resolution." 
  A joint statement confirming this has been signed in Gorazde 
by representatives of UNPROFOR [UN Protection Force] and the 
Muslim side, Williams said. A meeting between Yasushi Akashi, 
the UN secretary general's special envoy, and the vice president 
of the Croat-Muslim Federation will be held in the Palais des 
Nations first. The talks between the warring sides should 
follow. 

</TEXT>

