<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meetings, Talks on Bosnia Continue in Geneva </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meetings, Talks on Bosnia Continue in Geneva </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Akashi Notes Serb Withdrawal </H4>

<F P=102> LD0606105394 Belgrade TANJUG in English 0958 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0606105394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Geneva, June 6 (TANJUG) -- U.N. envoy to former 
Yugoslavia Yasushi Akashi said on Monday morning that all 
conditions had been created for Bosnia's belligerents to sit 
down at the conference table after armed Bosnian Serbs had 
withdrawn from the last controversial ridge around the Muslim 
enclave of Gorazde in the east. 
  The latest reports from the U.N. Protection Force (UNPROFOR) 
Command in Gorazde said that Bosnian Serb troops have withdrawn 
from the exclusion zone around the town, said Akashi. He 
explained that available information seemed to indicate that the 
conference might begin on Monday morning. 
  U.N. Secretary-general Butrus Butrus-Ghali arrived in Geneva 
during the night, in an effort to use his authority to help 
surmount controversial issues and finally open the conference on 
a general cessation of hostilities in Bosnia. 
  On Sunday night, Akashi had separate meetings with the 
Bosnian Serb and Muslim delegations, and indicated a certain 
reconciliation of stands from which it appeared that the 
conference might be held after all, after four days of delay. 
He said, however, that the Muslim side was still making its 
attendance conditional on receiving a report from its observers 
confirming that "armed Serb elements" had withdrawn from the 
exclusion zone around Gorazde. 
  In his most recent statement, Akashi said that the three 
sides were coming to the talks with different positions, but 
were willing that the conference, called at Geneva's Palais des 
Nations, should finally begin. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

