<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputies on Rejection of Road Sign Bill </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Deputies on Rejection of Road Sign Bill </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0306183194 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1500 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0306183194 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1500 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Slovak </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] As we have already reported in our previous 
bulletins, the National Council of the Slovak Republic today 
rejected the so-called road sign bill initiated by the 
government. According to Deputy Speaker Peter Weiss, it was 
shown that extremists on both sides were incapable of reaching a 
compromise agreement. He went on to remark that the bill had 
taken into account all of the most important amendments, 
including those made by the opposition. 
  Tibor Cabaj, deputy for the Movement for a Democratic 
Slovakia, said that sound reason had prevailed. According to 
him, the bill had not been well prepared, and, when amendments 
that had been submitted to improve it had failed to be 
incorporated, the way the opposition would vote had been quite 
clear. On the other hand, Vladimir Miskovsky, deputy for the 
National Democratic Party, was of the opinion that the 
amendments submitted had improved the bill to such an extent 
that it ought to have accommodated all tolerant people, both the 
Hungarian minority and the Slovaks living in the south of the 
country. Jan Carnogursky, chairman of the Christian Democratic 
Movement, saw the reason for the rejection of the bill in the 
fact that towns named after important Slovak figures had been 
excluded from the requirement to display bilingual signs. Pal 
Csaky, deputy for the Hungarian Christian Democratic 
Movement-Coexistence, commented on the rejection of the bill by 
saying that the matter was serious and that the party would draw 
conclusions from the breaking of the coalition agreement. Arpad 
Duka Zolyomi, representing the same party, had envisaged that 
the coalition partners would ensure the implementation of the 
agreement reached in the coalition council. He said that it 
would obviously be necessary to hold discussions about further 
cooperation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

