<H3> <TI>   Meetings, Talks on Bosnia Continue in Geneva </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meetings, Talks on Bosnia Continue in Geneva </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Buha Rejects Contact Group Maps </H4>

<F P=102> LD0406164594 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1548 GMT 4 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0406164594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, 4 Jun (TANJUG) -- The first round of the 
working consultations on the territorial division of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina between representatives of the three warring 
sides and the Contact Group has ended in the French Embassy in 
Geneva. 
  The maps, offered on the basis of drawings by a group of 
experts in Washington, are the maps for war, not for peace, 
Aleksa Buha, foreign minister for the Srpska republic, told 
journalists from TANJUG and Serb Sarajevo Radio-Television. The 
maps give 51 percent of Bosnian territory to the Muslims and 
Croats, and 49 percent to the Serbs, as proposed in the 
declaration adopted in Geneva on 13 May. But according to Buha, 
the talks should start with the percentage agreed upon within 
the Owen-Stoltenberg plan, which is 30 percent for the Muslims, 
16.5 for the Croats, and 53.5 for the Serbs. 
  The maps currently on offer have turned the Srpska republic 
into separate unconnected areas, which suggests the Muslim 
concept of a unitary Bosnia-Herzegovina, which is absolutely 
unacceptable for the Serb side, Buha said. 
  Talking about the end of the first round of talks, Srpska 
republic president Radovan Karadzic said that during the 
exchange of opinions, it became obvious that the Contact Group 
favored the Muslim side. 
  The talks on the cessation of hostilities have not yet 
started in the Palais des Nations in Geneva. A Srpska republic 
delegation has arrived in the Palais and is waiting for the 
arrival of the Muslim and Croat delegations who have been 
invited to the meeting by UN Special Envoy Yasushi Akashi after 
the news that the Serbs had withdrawn from the 3-km zone around 
Gorazde. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

