<F P=100> SLOVENIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Drnovsek Warns Croatia Over Border Problems </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Drnovsek Warns Croatia Over Border Problems </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0306152694 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1350 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0306152694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ljubljana, 3 Jun (TANJUG) -- Slovene Prime Minister 
Janez Drnovsek has warned the Croatian leadership that Slovenia 
will make "some political moves" unless Zagreb accepts 
Ljubljana's demands for the resolution of the problem of the 
state border between the two former Yugoslav republics. 
  The Croatian Government last night rejected the Slovene 
Foreign Ministry's proposal that Slovenia take over full control 
of the Bay of Piran, and Croatia continue the building of the 
Secovje border crossing near Portoroz. On this occasion, 
Drnovsek threatened to cancel the official visit of Slovene 
President Milan Kucan to Croatia and place the Secovje border 
crossing down the list of priorities. 
  Despite the claims of Prime Minister Drnovsek that Slovenia 
is opposed to a further exacerbation of relations, the official 
cancellation of Kucan's visit to Zagreb, scheduled for 7 June, 
is expected soon. The failure of the Slovene president to 
depart for Zagreb would represent yet another diplomatic clash 
between Ljubljana and Zagreb, which until recently were firm 
allies, and mutual relations would fall to an ever lower level. 

</TEXT>

