<H3> <TI>   Institute Manufacturing Tank Laser Range-Finder </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Institute Manufacturing Tank Laser Range-Finder </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0306094194 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 0820 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0306094194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Belgrade, 3 Jun (TANJUG) -- The Federal Republic 
of Yugoslavia has joined a small number of countries 
manufacturing tank laser range-finders. They are produced from 
local components and using state-of-the-art scientific and 
technical methods, Dr. Radovan Antanasijevic of the Zemun 
Physics Institute has said. 
  Dr. Antanasijevic, director of the center for applied 
Physics 
at the Zemun Institute, told a TANJUG correspondent that the 
Institute has developed and manufactured the tank laser 
range-finder within less than a year, despite the shortage of 
documentation and equipment. 
  The laser range-finder is a complex optical electronic 
system, used as part of modern combat equipment for defining the 
distance of the target quickly and with precision. The 
probability of hitting the target at first attempt is over 70 
percent, due to the application of laser and other 
state-of-the-art range measuring and information processing 
systems. 
  The range-finder produced in Yugoslavia measures distances 
of 
up to 10,000 meters, with an error margin of five meters. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

